4
00:00:20,500 --> 00:00:38,288
But the leading matter of it requires to be still further and more familiarly enlarged upon, in order to be adequately understood, and moreover to take away any incredulity which a profound ignorance of the entire subject may induce in some minds, as to the natural verity of the main points of this affair.

5
00:00:38,949 --> 00:00:41,833
I care not to perform this part of my task methodically.

6
00:00:42,168 --> 00:00:56,464
but shall be content to produce the desired impression by separate citations of items, practically or reliably known to me as a whaleman, and from these citations, I take it, the conclusion aimed at will naturally follow of itself.

7
00:00:56,680 --> 00:01:16,204
First, I have personally known three instances where a whale, after receiving a harpoon, has effected a complete escape and, after an interval in one instance of three years, has been again struck by the same hand and slain when the two irons, both marked by the same private cipher, have been taken from the body.

8
00:01:16,224 --> 00:01:23,953
In the instance where three years intervened between the flinging of the two harpoons, and I think it may have been something more than that,

9
00:01:24,423 --> 00:01:47,781
The man who darted them happening, in the interval, to go in a trading ship on a voyage to Africa, went ashore there, joined a discovery party, and penetrated far into the interior where he travelled for a period of nearly two years, often endangered by serpents, savages, tigers, poisonous miasmas, with all the other common perils incident to wandering in the heart of unknown regions.

10
00:01:47,761 --> 00:01:51,468
Meanwhile, the whale he had struck must also have been on its travels.

11
00:01:51,928 --> 00:01:58,600
No doubt it had thrice circumnavigated the globe, brushing with its flanks all the coasts of Africa, but to no purpose.

12
00:01:59,402 --> 00:02:03,629
This man and this whale again came together, and the one vanquished the other.

13
00:02:04,371 --> 00:02:11,203
I say I, myself, have known three instances similar to this, that is, in two of them.

14
00:02:11,386 --> 00:02:20,991
I saw the whale struck, and, upon the second attack, saw the two irons with the respective marks cut in them, afterwards taken from the dead fish.

15
00:02:21,292 --> 00:02:34,596
In the three-year instance, it so fell out that I was in the boat both times, first and last, and the last time distinctly recognized a peculiar sort of huge mole under the whale's eye, which I had observed there three years previous.

16
00:02:35,357 --> 00:02:38,563
I say three years, but I am pretty sure it was more than that.

17
00:02:39,244 --> 00:02:44,093
Here are three instances, then, which I personally know the truth of.

18
00:02:44,073 --> 00:02:50,620
but I have heard of many other instances from persons whose veracity in the matter there is no good ground to impeach.

19
00:02:51,822 --> 00:03:06,638
Secondly, it is well known in the sperm whale fishery, however ignorant the world ashore may be of it, that there have been several memorable historical instances where a particular whale in the ocean has been at distant times in places popularly cognizable.

20
00:03:07,057 --> 00:03:15,007
Why such a whale became thus marked was not altogether and originally owing to his bodily peculiarities as distinguished from other whales.

21
00:03:15,628 --> 00:03:26,803
For however peculiar in that respect any chance whale may be, they soon put an end to his peculiarities by killing him and boiling him down into a peculiarly valuable oil.

22
00:03:26,843 --> 00:03:30,027
No, the reason was this.

23
00:03:30,007 --> 00:03:48,270
that from the fatal experiences of the fishery there hung a terrible prestige of perilousness about such a whale as there did about Rinaldo Rinaldini, insomuch that most fishermen were content to recognize him by merely touching their tarpaulins when he would be discovered lounging by them on the sea, without seeking to cultivate a more intimate acquaintance.

24
00:03:48,830 --> 00:03:59,203
Like some poor devils ashore that happen to know an irascible great man, they make distant unobtrusive salutations to him in the street, lest if they pursued the acquaintance further

25
00:03:59,183 --> 00:04:01,945
they might receive a summary thump for their presumption.

26
00:04:02,606 --> 00:04:24,925
But not only did each of these famous whales enjoy great individual celebrity, nay, you may call it an ocean-wide renown, not only was he famous in life and now is immortal in forecastle stories after death, but he was admitted into all the rights, privileges, and distinctions of a name, had as much a name indeed as Cambyses or Caesar.

27
00:04:25,606 --> 00:04:28,228
Was it not so, O Timor-Tam?

28
00:04:28,208 --> 00:04:37,763
Thou famed Leviathan, scarred like an iceberg, who so long didst lurk in the oriental straits of that name, whose spout was off-seen from the palmy beach of Ombe.

29
00:04:38,584 --> 00:04:41,369
Was it not so, O New Zealand Jack?

30
00:04:41,389 --> 00:04:45,415
Thou terror of all cruisers that crossed their wakes in the vicinity of the Tattoo Land.

31
00:04:46,116 --> 00:04:47,719
Was it not so, O Morquan?

32
00:04:48,560 --> 00:04:55,431
King of Japan, whose lofty jet they say at times assumed the semblance of a snow-white cross against the sky.

33
00:04:55,411 --> 00:05:03,548
Was it not so, O Don Miguel, thou Chilean whale, Mark'd like an old tortoise with mystic hieroglyphics upon the back?

34
00:05:04,034 --> 00:05:12,004
In plain prose, here are four whales as well known to the students of cetacean history as Marius or Scylla to the classic scholar.

35
00:05:12,504 --> 00:05:13,726
But this is not all.

36
00:05:14,206 --> 00:05:14,887
New Zealand.

37
00:05:15,568 --> 00:05:32,488
Tom and Don Miguel, after at various times creating great havoc among the boats of different vessels, were finally gone in quest of, systematically hunted out, chased and killed by valiant whaling captains, who heaved up their anchors with that express object as much in view

38
00:05:32,468 --> 00:05:43,782
As in setting out through the Narragansett woods, Captain Butler of old had it in his mind to capture that notorious, murderous, savage Onewan, the headmost warrior of the Indian King Philip.

39
00:05:44,322 --> 00:06:01,243
I do not know where I can find a better place than just here, to make mention of one or two other things, which to me seem important, as in printed form, establishing in all respects the reasonableness of the whole story of the White Whale, more especially the catastrophe.

40
00:06:01,578 --> 00:06:06,987
For this is one of those disheartening instances where truth requires full as much bolstering as error.

41
00:06:07,929 --> 00:06:25,560
So ignorant are most landsmen of some of the plainest and most palpable wonders of the world, that without some hints touching the plain facts, historical and otherwise, of the fishery, they might scout at Moby Dick as a monstrous fable, or still worse and more detestable, a hideous and intolerable allegory.

42
00:06:25,540 --> 00:06:36,516
First, though most men have some vague, flitting ideas of the general perils of the grand fishery, yet they have nothing like a fixed, vivid conception of those perils, and the frequency with which they recur.

43
00:06:37,277 --> 00:06:48,393
One reason, perhaps, is that not one in fifty of the actual disasters and deaths by casualties in the fishery ever finds a public record at home, however transient, and immediately forgotten that record.

44
00:06:48,954 --> 00:06:55,243
Do you suppose that that poor fellow there, who this moment perhaps caught by the whale line off the coast of New Guinea,

45
00:06:55,223 --> 00:06:59,210
is being carried down to the bottom of the sea by the sounding Leviathan?

46
00:07:00,152 --> 00:07:07,305
Do you suppose that that poor fellow's name will appear in the newspaper obituary you will read to, morrow at your breakfast?

47
00:07:07,325 --> 00:07:11,453
No, because the mails are very irregular between here and New Guinea.

48
00:07:12,314 --> 00:07:18,666
In fact, did you ever hear what might be called regular news direct or indirect from New Guinea?

49
00:07:18,781 --> 00:07:32,865
Yet I tell you that upon one particular voyage which I made to the Pacific, among many others, we spoke thirty different ships, every one of which had had a death by a whale, some of them more than one, and three that had each lost a boat's crew.

50
00:07:32,926 --> 00:07:37,073
For God's sake, be economical with your lamps and candles.

51
00:07:37,754 --> 00:07:42,983
Not a gallon you burn, but at least one drop of man's blood was spilled for it.

52
00:07:42,963 --> 00:07:50,244
Secondly, people ashore have indeed some indefinite idea that a whale is an enormous creature of enormous power.

53
00:07:51,006 --> 00:07:57,124
But I have ever found that when narrating to them some specific example of this twofold enormousness,

54
00:07:57,222 --> 00:08:00,408
They have significantly complimented me upon my facetiousness.

55
00:08:01,009 --> 00:08:08,602
When, I declare upon my soul, I had no more idea of being facetious than Moses when he wrote the history of the plagues of Egypt.

56
00:08:09,324 --> 00:08:16,176
But fortunately the special point I here seek can be established upon testimony entirely independent of my own.

57
00:08:16,662 --> 00:08:17,745
That point is this.

58
00:08:18,386 --> 00:08:29,375
The sperm whale is in some cases sufficiently powerful, knowing, and judiciously malicious, as with direct aforethought to stave in, utterly destroy, and sink a large ship.

59
00:08:29,576 --> 00:08:32,443
And what is more, the sperm whale has done it.

60
00:08:32,423 --> 00:08:39,014
First, in the year 1820, the ship Essex, Captain Pollard of Nantucket, was cruising in the Pacific Ocean.

61
00:08:39,054 --> 00:08:44,644
One day she saw spouts, lowered her boats, and gave chase to a shoal of sperm whales.

62
00:08:45,245 --> 00:08:54,381
Ere long, several of the whales were wounded, when, suddenly, a very large whale escaping from the boats issued from the shoal and bore directly down upon the ship.

63
00:08:54,361 --> 00:09:00,590
Dashing his forehead against her hull, he so stove her in that in less than ten minutes she settled down and fell over.

64
00:09:00,931 --> 00:09:03,314
Not a surviving plank of her has been seen since.

65
00:09:03,915 --> 00:09:08,402
After the severest exposure, part of the crew reached the land in their boats.

66
00:09:09,343 --> 00:09:15,492
Being returned home at last, Captain Pollard once more sailed for the Pacific in command of another ship.

67
00:09:15,472 --> 00:09:19,278
But the gods shipwrecked him again upon unknown rocks and breakers.

68
00:09:19,779 --> 00:09:24,586
For the second time his ship was utterly lost, and forthwith forswearing the sea.

69
00:09:25,027 --> 00:09:26,509
He has never tempted it since.

70
00:09:27,450 --> 00:09:30,395
At this day Captain Pollard is a resident of Nantucket.

71
00:09:30,876 --> 00:09:35,603
I have seen Owen Chase, who was chief mate of the Essex at the time of the tragedy.

72
00:09:36,003 --> 00:09:38,207
I have read his plain and faithful narrative.

73
00:09:38,728 --> 00:09:44,196
I have conversed with his son, and all this within a few miles of the scene of the catastrophe.

74
00:09:44,176 --> 00:09:46,780
The following are extracts from Chase's narrative.

75
00:09:47,201 --> 00:09:52,409
Every fact seemed to warrant me in concluding that it was anything but chance which directed his operations.

76
00:09:52,990 --> 00:10:10,639
He made two several attacks upon the ship, at a short interval between them, both of which, according to their direction, were calculated to do us the most injury, by being made ahead, and thereby combining the speed of the two objects for the shock, to effect which, the exact maneuvers which he made were necessary.

77
00:10:10,619 --> 00:10:15,172
His aspect was most horrible, and such as indicated resentment and fury.

78
00:10:15,192 --> 00:10:23,937
He came directly from the shoal which we had just before entered, and in which we had struck three of his companions, as if fired with revenge for their sufferings.

79
00:10:24,355 --> 00:10:43,950
Again, at all events the whole circumstance is taken together, all happening before my own eyes, and producing, at the time, impressions in my mind of decided, calculating mischief, on the part of the whale, many of which impressions I cannot now recall, induce me to be satisfied that I am correct in my opinion.

80
00:10:43,930 --> 00:10:52,624
Here are his reflections some time after quitting the ship, during a black night, an open boat, when almost despairing of reaching any hospitable shore.

81
00:10:53,185 --> 00:10:55,749
The dark ocean and swelling waters were nothing.

82
00:10:56,269 --> 00:11:08,689
The fears of being swallowed up by some dreadful tempest, or dashed upon hidden rocks, with all the other ordinary subjects of fearful contemplation, seemed scarcely entitled to a moment's thought.

83
00:11:08,669 --> 00:11:17,244
the dismal-looking wreck and the horrid aspect, and revenge of the whore, wholly engrossed my reflections until day again made its appearance.

84
00:11:18,186 --> 00:11:19,989
In another place, p.

