86
00:11:25,358 --> 00:11:33,896
Secondly, the ship union, also of Nantucket, was in the year 1807 totally lost off the Azores by a similar onset.

87
00:11:34,297 --> 00:11:43,215
But the authentic particulars of this catastrophe I have never chanced to encounter, though from the whale hunters I have now and then heard casual allusions to it.

88
00:11:43,195 --> 00:11:58,183
Thirdly, some 18 or 20 years ago Commodore Jay, then commanding an American sloop of war of the first class, happened to be dining with a party of whaling captains on board a Nantucket ship in the harbor of Oahu, Sandwich Islands.

89
00:11:58,535 --> 00:12:06,549
Conversation turning upon whales, the Commodore was pleased to be skeptical touching the amazing strength ascribed to them by the professional gentleman present.

90
00:12:07,270 --> 00:12:15,565
He peremptorily denied, for example, that any whale could so smite his stout sloop of war as to cause her to leak so much as a thimbleful.

91
00:12:15,545 --> 00:12:17,709
Very good, but there is more coming."

92
00:12:18,610 --> 00:12:22,878
Some weeks after, the Commodore set sail in this impregnable craft for Valparaiso.

93
00:12:23,519 --> 00:12:28,848
But he was stopped on the way by a portly sperm whale that begged a few moments' confidential business with him.

94
00:12:28,868 --> 00:12:38,565
That business consisted in fetching the Commodore's craft such a thlack that with all his pumps going he made straight for the nearest port to heave down and repair.

95
00:12:38,545 --> 00:12:43,370
I am not superstitious, but I consider the Commodore's interview with that whale as providential.

96
00:12:43,930 --> 00:12:47,634
Was not Saul of Tarsus converted from unbelief by a similar fright?

97
00:12:48,214 --> 00:12:51,177
I tell you, the sperm whale will stand no nonsense.

98
00:12:51,778 --> 00:12:58,844
I will now refer you to Langsdorff's voyages for a little circumstance in point, peculiarly interesting to the writer hereof.

99
00:12:59,725 --> 00:13:08,113
Langsdorff, you must know by the way, was attached to the Russian Admiral Krusenstern's famous discovery expedition in the beginning of the present century.

100
00:13:08,093 --> 00:13:11,018
Captain Langsdorff thus begins his 17th chapter.

101
00:13:11,739 --> 00:13:18,170
By the 13th of May our ship was ready to sail and the next day we were out in the open sea on our way to Ochochish.

102
00:13:18,952 --> 00:13:25,984
The weather was very clear and fine, but so intolerably cold that we were obliged to keep on our fur clothing.

103
00:13:26,352 --> 00:13:28,215
For some days we had very little wind.

104
00:13:28,695 --> 00:13:32,461
It was not till the nineteenth that a brisk gale from the northwest sprang up.

105
00:13:33,042 --> 00:13:47,263
An uncommon large whale, the body of which was larger than the ship itself, lay almost at the surface of the water, but was not perceived by anyone on board till the moment when the ship, which was in full sail, was almost upon him.

106
00:13:47,243 --> 00:13:50,286
so that it was impossible to prevent its striking against him.

107
00:13:50,707 --> 00:13:59,817
We were thus placed in the most imminent danger, as this gigantic creature, setting up its back, raised the ship three feet at least out of the water.

108
00:14:00,758 --> 00:14:09,968
The masts reeled and the sails fell all together, while we who were below all sprang instantly upon the deck, concluding that we had struck upon some rock.

109
00:14:10,788 --> 00:14:15,934
Instead of this, we saw the monster sailing off with the utmost gravity and solemnity.

110
00:14:16,083 --> 00:14:25,977
Captain DeWolf applied immediately to the pumps to examine whether or not the vessel had received any damage from the shock, but we found that, very happily, it had escaped entirely uninjured.

111
00:14:26,878 --> 00:14:39,175
Now, the Captain DeWolf here alluded to as, commanding the ship in question, is a New Englander who, after a long life of unusual adventures as a sea captain, this day resides in the village of Dorchester near Boston.

112
00:14:39,215 --> 00:14:42,259
I have the honor of being a nephew of his.

113
00:14:42,931 --> 00:14:46,716
I have particularly questioned him concerning this passage in Langsdorf.

114
00:14:47,577 --> 00:14:49,159
He substantiates every word.

115
00:14:49,920 --> 00:14:59,754
The ship, however, was by no means a large one, a Russian craft built on the Siberian coast and purchased by my uncle after bartering away the vessel in which he sailed from home.

116
00:15:00,415 --> 00:15:11,790
In that up-and-down manly book of old-fashioned adventure, so full, too, of honest wonders, the voyage of Lionel Wafer, one of ancient Dampier's old chums,

117
00:15:11,905 --> 00:15:20,659
I found a little matter set down so like the just quoted from Langsdorff that I cannot forbear inserting it here for a corroborative example, if such be needed.

118
00:15:21,480 --> 00:15:26,508
Lionel, it seems, was on his way to John Ferdinando, as he calls the modern Juan Fernandez.

119
00:15:27,049 --> 00:15:29,172
In our way thither, he says.

120
00:15:29,152 --> 00:15:42,446
About four o'clock in the morning, when we were about 150 leagues from the main of America, our ship felt a terrible shock, which put our men in such consternation that they could hardly tell where they were or what to think.

121
00:15:43,086 --> 00:15:45,248
But everyone began to prepare for death.

122
00:15:46,289 --> 00:15:52,736
And, indeed, the shock was so sudden and violent that we took it for granted the ship had struck against a rock.

123
00:15:53,197 --> 00:15:58,602
But when the amazement was a little over, we cast the lead and sounded, but found no ground.

124
00:15:59,273 --> 00:16:05,013
The suddenness of the shock made the guns leap in their carriages, and several of the men were shaken out of their hammocks.

125
00:16:05,595 --> 00:16:09,469
Captain Davis, who lay with his head on a gun, was thrown out of his cabin.

126
00:16:09,753 --> 00:16:21,190
Lionel then goes on to impute the shock to an earthquake and seems to substantiate the imputation by stating that a great earthquake, somewhere about that time, did actually do great mischief along the Spanish land.

127
00:16:21,871 --> 00:16:31,264
But I should not much wonder if, in the darkness of that early hour of the morning, the shock was after all caused by an unseen whale vertically bumping the hull from beneath.

128
00:16:32,066 --> 00:16:35,811
I might proceed with several more examples, one way or another known to me,

129
00:16:35,791 --> 00:16:38,674
of the great power and malice at times of the sperm whale.

130
00:16:39,235 --> 00:16:50,547
In more than one instance, he has been known, not only to chase the assailing boats back to their ships, but to pursue the ship itself, and long withstand all the lances hurled at him from its decks.

131
00:16:51,308 --> 00:17:01,900
The English ship Pousey Hall can tell a story on that head, and, as for his strength, let me say, that there have been examples where the lines attached to a running sperm whale have,

132
00:17:01,880 --> 00:17:11,130
in a calm, been transferred to the ship and secured there, the whale towing her great hull through the water as a horse walks off for the cart.

133
00:17:11,228 --> 00:17:18,738
Again, it is very often observed that, if the sperm whale, once struck, is allowed time to rally, he then acts.

134
00:17:19,339 --> 00:17:25,047
Not so often with blind rage, as with willful, deliberate designs of destruction to his pursuers.

135
00:17:25,527 --> 00:17:36,983
Nor is it without conveying some eloquent indication of his character, that upon being attacked he will frequently open his mouth and retain it in that dread expansion for several consecutive minutes.

136
00:17:36,963 --> 00:18:00,997
But I must be content with only one more and a concluding illustration, a remarkable and most significant one, by which you will not fail to see, that not only is the most marvelous event in this book corroborated by plain facts of the present day, but that these marvels, like all marvels, are mere repetitions of the ages, so that for the millionth time we say, Amen with Solomon.

137
00:18:01,878 --> 00:18:04,742
Verily there is nothing new under the sun,

138
00:18:04,722 --> 00:18:13,967
In the 6th Christian century lived Procopius, a Christian magistrate of Constantinople, in the days when Justinian was emperor and Belisarius general.

139
00:18:14,710 --> 00:18:20,706
As many know, he wrote the history of his own times, a work every way of uncommon value.

140
00:18:20,838 --> 00:18:31,968
By the best authorities, he has always been considered a most trustworthy and unexaggerating historian, except in some one or two particulars, not at all affecting the matter presently to be mentioned.

141
00:18:32,609 --> 00:18:48,803
Now, in this history of his, Procopius mentions that, during the term of his prefecture at Constantinople, a great sea monster was captured in the neighboring Propontis, or Sea of Marmora, after having destroyed vessels at intervals in those waters for a period of more than fifty years.

142
00:18:48,783 --> 00:18:58,918
A fact thus set down in substantial history cannot easily be gainsaid, nor is there any reason it should be, of what precise species this sea monster was is not mentioned.

143
00:18:59,379 --> 00:19:09,795
But as he destroyed ships, as well as for other reasons, he must have been a whale, and I am strongly inclined to think a sperm whale, and I will tell you why.

144
00:19:10,180 --> 00:19:17,407
For a long time I fancied that the sperm whale had been always unknown in the Mediterranean and the deep waters connecting with it.

145
00:19:17,988 --> 00:19:28,378
Even now I am certain that those seas are not, and perhaps never can be, in the present constitution of things, a place for his habitual gregarious resort.

146
00:19:29,199 --> 00:19:38,668
But further investigations have recently proved to me that in modern times there have been isolated instances of the presence of the sperm whale in the Mediterranean.

147
00:19:38,783 --> 00:19:46,311
I am told, on good authority, that on the Barbary coast, a Commodore Davis of the British Navy found the skeleton of a sperm whale.

148
00:19:46,852 --> 00:19:55,381
Now, as a vessel of war readily passes through the Dardanelles, hence a sperm whale could, by the same route, pass out of the Mediterranean into the Perpontis.

149
00:19:56,182 --> 00:20:03,930
In the Perpontis, as far as I can learn, none of that peculiar substance called brit is to be found, the element of the right whale.

150
00:20:03,910 --> 00:20:16,244
But I have every reason to believe that the food of the sperm whale, squid, or cuttlefish lurks at the bottom of that sea, because large creatures, but by no means the largest of that sort, have been found at its surface."

151
00:20:16,945 --> 00:20:33,124
If, then, you properly put these statements together and reason upon them a bit, you will clearly perceive that, according to all human reasoning, Procopius's sea monster, that for half a century stove the ships of a Roman emperor, must in all probability have been a sperm whale.

